Here's an AP news story on Bob Hope just filed at 6:50 p.m. EST. I don't recall if it was him that I saw at the USO show in Da Nang, on November 29, 1967. It might have been. <br><br>
Bob Hope Stops by Vietnam Memorial<br><br>
By The Associated Press<br>
WASHINGTON (AP) -- America's newest veteran pressed his hand against the sun-warmed granite of the Vietnam Veteran's Memorial and marveled at the heat it held even after temperatures had started to drop Thursday afternoon. <br><br>
``Isn't that something,'' Bob Hope mused aloud. The memorial was Hope's first stop after President Clinton and Congress named him an honorary veteran for his half-century's work on behalf of the troops. Hope, 94, was in the Oval Office earlier Thursday when Clinton signed into law the bill that conferred veteran's status on the entertainer. <br><br>
``Bob Hope is a great American whose life has defined patriotism and service,'' Clinton said in a statement. ``In times of war and peace, good times and bad, he entertained our troops and brought to them a familiar and comforting sense of home while they defended our nation's interests around the world.'' <br><br>
Hope in 1979 publicly endorsed the idea of a Vietnam memorial and did public service advertisements promoting the project. He later signed a fund-raising letter that helped raise most of the money for the memorial. <br><br>
``He's the great hero of the Vietnam Veterans Memorial,'' said Jan Scruggs, president of the memorial fund. <br><br>
Tourists at the memorial dated themselves by their reactions to Hope. Older Americans who caught sight of the entertainer called out greetings, one yelling, ``We love you, Mr. Hope.'' Teen-agers wondered what all the commotion was about, asking one another, ``Who is he?'' <br><br>
Although in frail health, Hope showed he still knew the drill for a photo opportunity: As photographers snapped his picture at the memorial, he doffed his San Diego Chargers ballcap and quickly ran a comb through his hair. <br>

